<subSubSection pageId="63" pageNumber="64" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="63.[151,1437,987,1770]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1312,1338]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Remarks</emphasis>
. This species is not rare around 
<taxonomicName box="[686,974,1311,1337]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Filipendula" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="camtschatica">
<emphasis box="[686,974,1311,1337]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Filipendula camtschatica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
bushes in 
<collectingRegion box="[1100,1213,1311,1337]" country="Japan" name="Hokkaido" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Hokkaido</collectingRegion>
, where two species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1803" box="[183,311,1347,1373]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Pamphilius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[183,311,1347,1373]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Pamphilius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Smith, 1874)" authorityName="NSMT" baseAuthorityName="Smith" baseAuthorityYear="1874" box="[327,619,1347,1374]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Pamphilius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="venustus">
<emphasis box="[327,452,1348,1373]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">P. venustus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Smith, F." box="[469,610,1347,1374]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" pagination="373 - 409" refId="ref79508" refString="Smith, F. (1874) Descriptions of new species of Tenthredinidae, Ichneumonidae, Chrysididae, Formicidae &amp; c. of Japan. Transactions of the Entomological Society of London for the Year, 1874, 373 - 409. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1365 - 2311.1874. tb 00867. x" type="journal article" year="1874">Smith, 1874</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="(Matsumura, 1912)" baseAuthorityName="Matsumura" baseAuthorityYear="1912" box="[677,1066,1348,1374]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Pamphilius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sapporensis">
<emphasis box="[677,839,1348,1373]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">P. sapporensis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Matsumura, S." box="[855,1057,1348,1374]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" refId="ref74972" refString="Matsumura, S. (1912) Thousand Insects of Japan. Supplement IV. Keiseisha, Tokyo, 1 p. + 247 pp., 14 pls., 2 + 2 pp. [in Japanese and English]" type="book" year="1912">Matsumura, 1912</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
also occur together. These three pamphiliids are all associated with 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Kangas &amp; Syrjanen" baseAuthorityYear="1962" box="[545,676,1383,1409]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Filipendula" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[545,676,1383,1409]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Filipendula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="63.[151,1437,987,1770]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">
In the COI analysis (
<figureCitation box="[435,533,1419,1446]" captionStart="FIGURE 139" captionStartId="228.[151,250,1667,1691]" captionTargetBox="[157,1426,190,1638]" captionTargetId="figure-26@228.[151,1436,181,1643]" captionTargetPageId="228" captionText="FIGURE 139. Condensed ML tree based on CO1 gene sequences, with details of Onycholyda, part 2." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876841" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876841/files/figure.png" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Fig. 139</figureCitation>
), 
<specimenCount box="[554,735,1419,1445]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" type="generic">three specimens</specimenCount>
from 
<collectingRegion box="[804,914,1419,1445]" country="Japan" name="Hokkaido" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Hokkaido</collectingRegion>
(NSMT30554, 30788, 30789) and 
<specimenCount pageId="63" pageNumber="64" type="generic">four specimens</specimenCount>
from Honshu (NSMT30730, 30785–30787) each formed a different cluster and the two clusters had a sistergroup relationship supported by 100% UFBoot values. The maximum 
<emphasis box="[938,952,1492,1517]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">p</emphasis>
-distance in the 
<collectingRegion box="[1129,1239,1491,1517]" country="Japan" name="Hokkaido" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Hokkaido</collectingRegion>
cluster was 0.2% and that in the Honshu cluster was 1%. The minimum 
<emphasis box="[771,785,1528,1553]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">p</emphasis>
-distance between the Honshu and 
<collectingRegion box="[1181,1291,1527,1553]" country="Japan" name="Hokkaido" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Hokkaido</collectingRegion>
clusters was 2.2%. In the NaK tree (
<figureCitation box="[419,517,1563,1590]" captionStart="FIGURE 153" captionStartId="240.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[178,1407,186,1910]" captionTargetId="figure-26@240.[172,1415,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="240" captionText="FIGURE 153. Condensed ML tree based on NaK gene sequences, with details of Onycholyda." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876872" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876872/files/figure.png" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Fig. 153</figureCitation>
), the four Honshu specimens formed a cluster but the three 
<collectingRegion box="[1201,1311,1563,1589]" country="Japan" name="Hokkaido" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Hokkaido</collectingRegion>
specimens did not and, with the Honshu cluster, formed a polytomous clade, which was sister to 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Shinohara" authorityYear="1985" box="[1114,1229,1600,1626]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="armata">
<emphasis box="[1114,1229,1600,1626]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">O. armata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(this clade, 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Benes" authorityYear="1972" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kumamotonis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">O. kumamotonis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
+ 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Shinohara" authorityYear="1985" box="[303,417,1636,1662]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="armata">
<emphasis box="[303,417,1636,1662]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">O. armata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, was supported by 100% UFBoot value). The maximum 
<emphasis box="[1054,1068,1636,1661]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">p</emphasis>
-distance within 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Benes" authorityYear="1972" box="[1253,1436,1635,1662]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kumamotonis">
<emphasis box="[1253,1436,1635,1662]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">O. kumamotonis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was 0.4% and the nearest neighbour, diverging by a minimum of 0.2%, was 
<emphasis box="[1005,1128,1672,1698]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Shinohara" authorityYear="1985" box="[1005,1124,1672,1698]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="armata">O. armata</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
The 
<collectingRegion box="[1184,1294,1671,1697]" country="Japan" name="Hokkaido" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Hokkaido</collectingRegion>
and Honshu populations of 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Benes" authorityYear="1972" box="[318,501,1707,1734]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kumamotonis">
<emphasis box="[318,501,1707,1734]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">O. kumamotonis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
certainly have some genetic divergence, but we will leave them as one species until more evidence of speciation becomes available.
</paragraph>
